'''Ronwen Hayden Williams''' (born 21 January 1992) is a [[South Africa]]n professional [[Association football|footballer]] who plays as a [[Goalkeeper (association football)|goalkeeper]] for [[Premier Soccer League]] club [[Mamelodi Sundowns F.C.|Mamelodi Sundowns]] and [[Captain (association football)|captains]] the [[South Africa national soccer team|South Africa national team]].

He was ranked the ninth best goalkeeper in the world at the [[2024 Ballon d'Or]] awards.<ref>{{Cite web |date=2024-10-29 |title=Ronwen Williams places ninth for Yashin Trophy at Ballon d'Or awards {{!}} soccer |url=https://www.sabcsport.com/soccer/news/ronwen-williams-places-ninth-for-yashin-trophy-at-ballon-d-or-awards |access-date=2024-11-06 |website=SABC |language=en}}</ref>

== Club career ==
=== Early career ===
Williams spent part of his youth career with [[Premier League]] club [[Tottenham Hotspur F.C.|Tottenham Hotspur]].<ref>{{Cite web |last=Modise |first=Jimmy |date=2017-06-05 |title=7 Things You Didn't Know About Ronwen Williams |url=https://diski365.co.za/7-things-didnt-know-ronwen-williams/ |access-date=2022-07-25 |website=Diski 365 |language=en-US}}</ref>

=== SuperSport United ===
Williams joined [[SuperSport United F.C.|SuperSport United]] as a youth player in 2004. He made his debut in the [[CAF Champions League]] in January 2012 against [[Matlama FC]], and in the [[Premier Soccer League|PSL]] four months later against [[Free State Stars F.C.|Free State Stars]]. He kept clean sheets in both games.<ref>{{Cite web |title=SuperSport |url=https://supersport.com/football/dstv-premiership/news/b03ab23c-5b41-49d3-a737-36bfb3edc12f/%7B%7B%20url()-%3Ecurrent()%20%7D%7D |access-date=2022-07-25 |website=supersport.com |language=}}</ref>

=== Mamelodi Sundowns ===
On 21 July 2022, Williams signed with [[Mamelodi Sundowns F.C.|Mamelodi Sundowns]] after a 12-year career at SuperSport United.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Mamelodi Sundowns {{!}} Ronwen Williams Joins Masandawana! |url=https://sundownsfc.co.za/media/mamelodi-sundowns-ronwen-williams-joins-masandawana/ |access-date=2022-07-25 |website=Mamelodi Sundowns {{!}} Official Website |language=en-US}}</ref> He made his debut in the 2022–23 opener against [[Cape Town City FC]] where he made a string of great saves and kept a clean sheet.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Mamelodi Sundowns 2-0 Cape Town City (5 Aug, 2022) Final Score – ESPN (UK) |url=https://www.espn.co.uk/football/match/_/gameId/649351 |access-date=2024-02-08 |website=ESPN |language=en}}</ref> He won the [[African Football League]] with Mamelodi Sundowns in 2023 where he made two important penalties saves one against Al Ahly and the other one against CA Petróleos Luanda.

On 17 June 2025, Williams became the first player penalized under FIFA's new eight-second ball possession rule when he held onto the ball for 14 seconds. The rule was enforced for the first time during the [[FIFA Club World Cup]] match against South Korea's [[Ulsan HD FC|Ulsan Hyundai]].<ref>{{Cite web |date=2025-06-20 |title=Club World Cup 2025: Tournament's new innovations to football |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/articles/cdx5r85yng9o |access-date=2025-06-23 |website=BBC Sport |language=en-GB}}</ref>

==International career==
Williams made his first appearance for [[South Africa national football team|South Africa]] on 5 March 2014, in a friendly against [[Brazil national football team|Brazil]], due to a sprained ankle suffered by the first-choice keeper, [[Itumeleng Khune]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.enca.com/sport-soccer/williams-set-dream-bafana-debut |title=Williams set for dream Bafana debut |publisher=eNCA |access-date=2014-03-05}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.thenewage.co.za/120371-10-53-Williams_makes_international_debut |title=Williams makes international debut &#124; The New Age Online |publisher=Thenewage.co.za |access-date=2014-03-05 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140305220233/http://www.thenewage.co.za/120371-10-53-Williams_makes_international_debut |archive-date=5 March 2014}}</ref>

In August 2021, the new South Africa coach [[Hugo Broos]] named Williams as the new ''Bafana Bafana'' captain, taking the armband from [[Thulani Hlatshwayo]] who failed to make the squad.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sowetanlive.co.za/sport/soccer/2021-08-30-broos-names-williams-as-bafana-bafana-skipper-tau-deputy-captain |title=Broos names Williams as Bafana Bafana skipper, Tau deputy captain |publisher=Sowetanlive |access-date=2021-10-12}}</ref>

On 3 February 2024, in South Africa's [[2023 Africa Cup of Nations|2023 AFCON]] quarter-final match against [[Cape Verde national football team|Cape Verde]], the game was drawn at 0–0 after extra time. Williams saved 4 penalties in the penalty shootout, taking ''Bafana Bafana'' through to an AFCON semi-final for the first time since 2000.<ref>{{Cite news |title=SA goalkeeper saves four penalties in shootout win |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/68115046 |access-date=2024-02-08 |work=BBC Sport |language=en-GB}}</ref> Although South Africa lost to [[Nigeria national football team|Nigeria]] in the semi-finals in another penalty shootout, Williams went ahead to win the [[Africa Cup of Nations awards#Best Goalkeeper|Best Goalkeeper]] of the tournament.<ref name="auto1"/>

On 1 December 2025, Williams was called up to the South Africa squad for the [[2025 Africa Cup of Nations]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cafonline.com/afcon2025/news/totalenergies-afcon-morocco-2025-fever-rises-as-broos-become-first-coach-to-unveil-final-squad/|title=TotalEnergies AFCON Morocco 2025 fever rises as Broos become first coach to unveil final squad|publisher=[[Confederation of African Football]]|date=1 December 2025|access-date=12 December 2025}}</ref>

